Thus we never find in Terence an ictus like sequimur or pectora or indictum. Indeed, the rnetrical ictnses of lines in comedy coincide pretty closely with the ordinary accentuation of words in everyday speech. Many words, we must remem- ber, are long enough to admit two accents,¹ eg. decreveram, econimcltus, ete. Further, the accent of a word in a sentence may be different from that which it bears when standing by itself. Thus the subordinate words in a sentence may unite with the ruore important ones to form word-groups, which then follow the ordinary rules of accentuation, eg. polizlspuom (21), adesdum (29), optol-me (36).
